t is Travelers’ Choice Best of the Best? This award is our highest recognition and is presented annually to those businesses that are the Best of the Best on Tripadvisor, those that earn excellent reviews from travelers and are ranked in the top 1% of properties worldwide. Learn more 2,912 Jamaica Save Is there anything better than swaying from a hammock in a warm patch of Jamaican sun? If you're seeking laid-back vibes, you've come to the right place. But Jamaica offers plenty of outdoor adventure for those that want it, too. Consider diving into Blue Hole, rafting on Martha Brae River, even bobsledding down Mystic Mountain. Fuel up on delicious, stick-to-your-ribs food like jerk chicken before exploring. It's also worth visiting the authentic music clubs of Kingston, especially for fans of reggae. Read more Essential Jamaica Pick a category to filter your recs Essentials Travelers' Choice Family friendly Hidden gems Museums Outdoors Arts & theater Nightlife Things to do See all Dunn's River Falls and Park 4.4 4.4 of 5 bubbles ( 20,427 ) Waterfalls, Zipline & Aerial Adventure Parks Seven Mile Beach 4.6 4.6 of 5 bubbles ( 8,143 ) Beaches Blue Hole 4.8 4.8 of 5 bubbles ( 7,234 ) Waterfalls Mesmerizing Luminous Lagoon (Glistening Waters) Night Tour 4.3 4.3 of 5 bubbles ( 89 ) Bob Marley Museum 4.3 4.3 of 5 bubbles ( 1,666 ) Speciality Museums YS Falls 4.6 4.6 of 5 bubbles ( 2,475 ) Water Parks Places to stay See all Excellence Oyster Bay 4.5 4.5 of 5 bubbles ( 8,372 ) from $682/night Round Hill Hotel and Villas 4.8 4.8 of 5 bubbles ( 1,929 ) from $1,046/night The Caves 4.8 4.8 of 5 bubbles ( 922 ) from $502/night Half Moon 4.7 4.7 of 5 bubbles ( 3,687 ) from $1,019/night Skylark Negril Beach Resort 4.9 4.9 of 5 bubbles ( 477 ) GoldenEye 4.7 4.7 of 5 bubbles ( 576 ) from $797/night Food & drink See all Zimbali's Mountain Cooking Studio 4.8 4.8 of 5 bubbles ( 836 ) $$$$ • Jamaican, Vegetarian friendly, Vegan options Blue Mahoe Restaurant 4.7 4.7 of 5 bubbles ( 654 ) $$ - $$$ • Caribbean, Seafood, International Fireman's Lobster Pit 4.7 4.7 of 5 bubbles ( 889 ) $$ - $$$ • Caribbean, Seafood, Jamaican Little Ochie 4.3 4.3 of 5 bubbles ( 264 ) $$ - $$$ • Caribbean, Seafood, Jamaican Kool Vybes Bar & Jerk Centre 4.8 4.8 of 5 bubbles ( 282 ) $ • Caribbean, Jamaican, Vegetarian friendly Scotchies 4.5 4.5 of 5 bubbles ( 3,811 ) $ • Caribbean, Barbecue, Jamaican Travel Advice Best time to visit Getting around Local customs Tips from the pros Traveler Guides The Best Things to Do in Jamaica 6 items By Clara S Keep Love Alive in Jamaica 14 items By Lara Grant The Best Family-friendly All-inclusives 7 items By Clara S Itineraries to help you plan Created by AI, guided by insights from our community. Learn more Couples Must-see Attractions Great Food 4 days in Jamaica for couples Powered by AI See itinerary Friends Reggae Music Culture Water Sports 5 days in Jamaica for friend groups Powered by AI Couples Water Sports Culture 7 days in Jamaica for couples Powered by AI Family Water Sports Arts & Theatre 6 days in Jamaica for families Powered by AI Best outdoor activities in Jamaica My first trip to Jamaica was all about romance—I had my honeymoon here. Since then, I’ve been back several times and have discovered the island’s more adventurous side. Beyond swimming and snorkeling, there’s everything from rafting down Martha Brae River to hiking the famous Blue Mountains. These are my favorite outdoor adventures in Jamaica. Mariette Williams Rick's Cafe 3.9 3.9 of 5 bubbles ( 5,662 ) You wouldn’t expect one of Jamaica’s most legendary hangouts to be tucked away in Negril, a sleepy beach town on the western end of the island. But for 50 years, people have flocked to Rick’s Cafe to catch the sunset and see the gravity-defying local cliff divers. You can get in on the action, too—there are several jumping spots for both experienced and novice divers. Blue Mountains 4.7 4.7 of 5 bubbles ( 424 ) Jamaica’s beloved Blue Mountain coffee isn’t the only thing this area is known for—it’s a haven for hikers as well. The most challenging trail ascends the 7,500-foot Blue Mountain Peak, the highest point in Jamaica. (On a clear day, you can even see Cuba!) The seven-mile trek is steep; expect it to take about seven hours. Tip: The hike is best done with a guide during the dry season from December to April. Martha Brae River 4.5 4.5 of 5 bubbles ( 2,000 ) Few things are as calming as floating on a bamboo raft down the Martha Brae River, between Ocho Rios and Montego Bay. Each raft is equipped with cushioned seats and comes with a guide who will expertly paddle your raft down the river. Bring a swimsuit and towel if you want to add on a limestone mud massage (it’s worth it). I suggest setting aside two hours total for the experience. Dunn's River Falls and Park 4.4 4.4 of 5 bubbles ( 20,427 ) Tourists and locals alike come to Dunn’s River Falls to soak in the natural pools and climb the rocky cascades (make sure you wear water shoes). While kids play at the splash park, adults can get an adrenaline rush on the zipline that soars above the falls. By late afternoon, Dunn’s River gets crowded with cruise ship passengers, so plan to arrive earlier to have the place to yourself. Green Grotto Caves 4.3 4.3 of 5 bubbles ( 729 ) Cool off by exploring the Green Grotto Caves, on the northern coast. The caves have a fascinating history—they were once a hideout for Jamaican Maroons (a community of escaped African slaves) and Arawak Indigenous people. Today, you can spend an hour or two exploring the stalagmites and stalactites with an experienced guide. You may even get an up-close encounter with the bats living in the caves. Seven Mile Beach 4.6 4.6 of 5 bubbles ( 8,143 ) Not to play favorites, but it’s pretty hard to beat Seven Mile Beach in Negril. You can spend a whole day lounging on this pristine stretch (don’t forget cash to rent chairs and an umbrella). The powdery white sand and tranquil water also make this beach ideal for snorkeling right off of the shore. Keep an eye out for angelfish, pufferfish, and stingrays. Blue Hole 4.8 4.8 of 5 bubbles ( 7,234 ) It’s obvious how this swimming hole in Ocho Rios got its name. The eye-popping limestone pool has some of the clearest turquoise water I’ve ever seen. Jump in from three staggered platforms, swing off a vine, or step right into the 20-foot deep natural pool. Or, hike 10 minutes to Secret Falls, which has a thundering cascade and shallower sections for wading. Just watch your step—the ground is quite slippery. How to do Jamaica in 2 days Beachfront snorkeling, wild river floating, and limestone mud spa treatments Read on Trending in the forums See all Help! Can't decide which couples resort? By Nature's B 7 replies Negril scuba, driving and authentic jerk! By miserkris 6 replies Cockroaches at Montego Bay Resorts By Winnipegger4 12 replies Jamaica Is Great For Beachside drinks and late-night dancing Floyd's Pelican Bar 4.5 4.5 of 5 bubbles ( 864 ) Bars & Clubs The Jungle Night Club, Sports Bar & Grill 4.1 4.1 of 5 bubbles ( 194 ) Dance Clubs & Discos Drifters Bar & Entertainment Venue 4.7 4.7 of 5 bubbles ( 151 ) Bars & Clubs, Concerts Rick's Cafe 4.0 4 of 5 bubbles ( 6,604 ) Bars & Clubs Collette's Bar 4.9 4.9 of 5 bubbles ( 124 ) Bars & Clubs One Love Bus Bar Crawl 4.8 4.8 of 5 bubbles ( 1,300 ) Bus Tours, Cultural Tours Canoe Bar 4.4 4.4 of 5 bubbles ( 473 ) $$ - $$$ • Caribbean, Bar, Seafood Alfred's Ocean Palace 4.1 4.1 of 5 bubbles ( 64 ) Cristal Nightclub 5.0 5 of 5 bubbles ( 9 ) Bars & Clubs Kingston Dub Club 4.6 4.6 of 5 bubbles ( 57 ) Bars & Clubs Soaking up Jamaican culture Bob Marley Museum 4.3 4.3 of 5 bubbles ( 1,666 ) Speciality Museums Rose Hall Great House 4.4 4.4 of 5 bubbles ( 2,907 ) Architectural Buildings, Historic Sites Rastafari Indigenous Village 4.7 4.7 of 5 bubbles ( 117 ) Historic Walking Areas Nine Miles 4.0 4 of 5 bubbles ( 966 ) Historic Sites, Points of Interest & Landmarks Devon House 4.4 4.4 of 5 bubbles ( 1,129 ) Historic Sites, Monuments & Statues Trench Town Community Tour 4.4 4.4 of 5 bubbles ( 190 ) Historic Walking Areas, Speciality Museums Surfing, sunbathing, and long naps on the beach Doctor's Cave Beach 4.2 4.2 of 5 bubbles ( 2,420 ) Beaches Frenchman's Cove 4.5 4.5 of 5 bubbles ( 1,018 ) Beaches Bloody Bay 4.6 4.6 of 5 bubbles ( 1,056 ) Beaches, Bodies of Water Seven Mile Beach 4.6 4.6 of 5 bubbles ( 8,143 ) Beaches Boston Beach 4.1 4.1 of 5 bubbles ( 340 ) Beaches Winifred Beach 4.5 4.5 of 5 bubbles ( 485 ) Beaches Explore more from our sponsors Jamaica Travel Guide Travelers' pro tips for experiencing Jamaica B S Get the real flavor of Jamaica through interactions with the friendly locals at shops, restaurants and bars. thevinnie Bring some cash. Some places take credit cards and some do not. In Jamaica some ATMs issue only Jamaican dollars, some issue only US dollars and some issue either currency (you need to specify which one you want). gdbear65 Rules of the road and local motoring etiquette are different. Jamaicans are very expressive with their horns. Polite beeps (a couple of taps) can mean “Hello”, “Thank You”, “Pay Attention” or “Let me pass”. Angry beeps or beeps expressing annoyance are longer and can mean you’re taking too long to react to a green light, make a turn or you’re holding up traffic. The horn is a form of communication, so please do not get angry or take offense when you hear someone honking at you. Wirtztlm Put on your Jamaica to-do list! elizabethcantoni Jamaica is beautiful and so are the people. IslandMama As they say: “Once you go, you know!” Christine C I have been to almost every part of Jamaica and Seven Mile Beach is by far the best location in all of Jamaica, the sunsets are incredible, the ocean is calm, the sand is soft and white. Ingrid P You can't go to Jamaica and not visit the Bob Marley Museum. Bob is a legend in Jamaica and part of their whole culture. What is the best way to get there? flying Jamaica is served by three international airports: Norman Manley International Airport in Kingston, Sangster International Airport in Montego Bay, and Ian Fleming International Airport close to Ocho Rios. Do I need a visa? If you’re visiting Jamaica from overseas, use this site to see if you need a visa. When is the best time to visit? Sunseekers will rarely be disappointed in Jamaica with daytime temperatures hovering between 77-86°F (25-30°C) all year-round. November to June brings the sunniest and driest weather, ideal for lazing on the beach or partying at a festival — top events include Carnival (April), Bob Marley Birthday Week (Feb) and Reggae Sumfest (July). Hurricane season runs from August to November, and it’s rainiest in September. However, if you don’t mind the daily showers, out-of-season travelers can pick up some good deals at the island’s resorts. Get around car Renting a car or motorbike can be a cost-effective choice for those wanting to explore multiple destinations. A 4WD is recommended if you’re heading out of the main towns, where roads are often unpaved and full of potholes. buses Knutsford Express operate regular buses between Kingston, Negril, Ocho Rios and other destinations around Jamaica. minibuses and shared taxis Minibuses and route taxis (shared taxis) are the most common way for locals to get around, linking towns, villages and beaches all around the country. Most have set routes, but no official timetables, so it’s best to enquire locally. ridesharing Uber and other ridesharing services are not currently available in Jamaica. On the ground What is the timezone? Eastern Standard Time What are the voltage/plug types? The standard voltage in Jamaica is 110 V and the standard frequency is 50 Hz. There are two plug types — one with two flat pins and another with two flat pins and a grounding pin What is the currency? Jamaican dollar (JMD); US dollars are also widely accepted. Are ATMs readily accessible? Yes, in all large towns and cities. Are credit cards widely accepted? Yes, especially around the main tourist resorts, but you will need cash at some smaller shops, restaurants and markets. How much do I tip? Tipping is not obligatory in Jamaica, however, a 10-15% tip for exceptional service is always appreciated. Restaurants: Some will add a 10% service charge as standard. Hotels/resorts: A US$1-2 tip for the bellman and housekeeper is appreciated. Spas: 10-15% Tour guides: 10-20% Taxi drivers: Drivers do not expect tips in Jamaica, but it’s nice to round up the fare. If drivers are particularly nice or helpful, 5% will suffice. Are there local customs I should know? Drinking: The federal legal age for buying and drinking alcohol is 18 years old. Marijuana: Marijuana use, sale and possession is illegal in Jamaica. Although steps have been made towards decriminalization, you will be fined for being in possession without a medical prescription. Drive on the left: If you hire a car, be aware that Jamaicans drive on the left side of the road. Similarly, when crossing the road, be sure to look to the right. Keep your clothes on!: Topless sunbathing is not generally acceptable in Jamaica and while you may find it’s tolerated at some resorts, it’s best to do as the locals do and keep covered. Water: Jamaica’s tap water is drinkable in all of the main cities and resorts, so bring a refillable water bottle. Learn the local lingo: Jamaica’s official language is English, but it’s often mixed with Jamaican Patois and is full of words and phrases unique to the island. Jamaica travel tips Powered by AI These questions and answers were created by AI, using the most common questions travelers ask in the forums. What are the best all-inclusive resorts in Jamaica? Popular Resorts According to forum posts, some of the best all-inclusive resorts in Jamaica include RIU Palace Tropical Bay, Hilton Rose Hall, and Sunscape. These resorts are recommended for their family-friendly amenities and activities. Additional Recommendations Travelers have called out Jewel Runaway Bay, Jewel Grande Montego Bay, and Royalton Blue Waters as excellent choices. These resorts are noted for their good beaches, pools, and inclusive activities suitable for families. Budget-Friendly Options For those looking to maximize their budget, forum users suggest considering the time of travel, as prices can vary significantly between the high and low season. Resorts like Iberostar Rose Hall and Royal Decameron Cornwall Beach are also recommended, especially if extending the stay to over five days to get better deals. Luxury and Adult Options For a more luxurious or adult-only experience, the Iberostar Grand and Hyatt Zilara come highly recommended. These resorts offer exclusive adult-only areas while providing options to visit family-friendly sections if needed. This summary was generated by AI from Tripadvisor forum posts. See related posts Was this helpful? What are popular beach destinations in Jamaica? Popular Beach Destinations According to forum posts, Negril is frequently mentioned as a popular beach destination in Jamaica, particularly for its Seven Mile Beach, known for its long stretches of sandy beaches and crystal-clear waters. Travelers have highlighted that Negril provides a good mix of accommodations, from all-inclusive resorts to boutique hotels, and offers various activities along the beach. Beach Activities and Features Some travelers said that Negril's beaches are not rocky, which makes them ideal for swimming and beach activities. The area is also noted for having minimal seaweed, ensuring a more pleasant beach experience. Additionally, the beaches in Negril are described as having a lively atmosphere with access to local pubs, bars, and live music venues. Alternative Beach Locations For users interested in surfing, forum posts suggest considering beaches near Kingston or the eastern part of the island. Boston Bay in Portland is specifically recommended for surfing, with available lessons and a less touristy vibe compared to more popular destinations like Negril. This summary was generated by AI from Tripadvisor forum posts. See related posts Was this helpful? What are some family-friendly accommodations in Jamaica? Family-Friendly Resorts Some travelers have recommended the Azul Beach Resort in Negril and Jewel Grande in Montego Bay for families, noting that these locations offer multi-bedroom accommodations suitable for larger families. However, opinions on Azul are mixed regarding its suitability for teenagers. All-Inclusive Options According to forum posts, family-friendly all-inclusive resorts such as the Hilton Rose Hall and Royalton Negril are popular choices. These resorts offer amenities like pools, activities, and multiple dining options that cater to families with children of various ages. Alternative Accommodations For those considering non-all-inclusive options, properties like Rondells with villas and the Treehouse, which offers beach suites in Negril, have been highlighted. These accommodations provide a more local experience with access to nearby activities and dining options suitable for families. Activity-Oriented Stays Travelers have also pointed out that resorts like Jewel Runaway Bay and the Franklin D Resort are tailored towards families, offering specific amenities like game rooms and activities that keep younger guests entertained. This summary was generated by AI from Tripadvisor forum posts. See related posts Was this helpful? What is the tipping etiquette in Jamaica? Tipping Policies According to forum posts, some resorts in Jamaica, such as Couples, Sandals, Beaches, and Hedonism II in Negril, strictly prohibit tipping as part of their policy. It is advised to inquire about the tipping policy upon arrival at your resort. Currency for Tipping Travelers have called out that both US dollars and Jamaican dollars are widely accepted for tipping in Jamaica. However, a preference for tipping in Jamaican dollars is expressed by some due to its convenience for local workers who might face difficulties exchanging US dollars. General Tipping Practice For many users, tipping is customary and appreciated, especially for service providers outside of resorts, such as tour guides, drivers, and waitstaff in local restaurants. Tips typically range from 15% to 25% in restaurants, and a few dollars for bag handlers or housekeeping staff per day. Observing Local Customs Some travelers said observing local customs and how others tip in Jamaica can be a good guide for appropriate tipping behavior. It is generally advised to tip in cash to ensure that the service staff receives it directly. This summary was generated by AI from Tripadvisor forum posts. See related posts Was this helpful? What are the best resorts in Negril for families? Popular Recommendations According to forum posts, Beaches Negril is highly recommended for families due to its comprehensive amenities that cater to children, including a waterpark and activities involving Sesame Street characters. However, it is noted for being pricey. Alternative Options Some travelers have suggested the Royalton Negril for its kid-friendly features like a splash activity pool. Additionally, the Azul Beach Resort is favored for its proximity to a potentially reopening water-based playground at Island Lux Beach Park. Both are considered good alternatives to Beaches Negril. Additional Considerations For those seeking more budget-friendly options, the Hilton Rose Hall in Montego Bay offers a lazy river and water slide, although its beach does not compare to those in Negril. Furthermore, travelers have mentioned that while the RIU resorts in Negril are close to attractions like the Kool Runnings Water Park, they may not offer the best customer service. This summary was generated by AI from Tripadvisor forum posts. See related posts Was this helpful? What are the best beachfront hotel options in Montego Bay? Beach Quality and Location According to forum posts, the S Hotel in Montego Bay is highly recommended for its prime location on a well-regarded section of the beach. It is praised for being modern and having a great beachfront, making it a popular choice among travelers looking for quality beach time. Facility and Services Some travelers have highlighted the Royal Decameron Cornwall Beach for its location on a natural sand beach, which is noted for being one of the better sections in Montego Bay. This resort is also appreciated for being smaller and more navigable, which could be beneficial for those who prefer less walking. Overall Experience The Riu Palace is mentioned as part of a complex of three resorts that share some facilities like spas, gyms, and water sports. Despite its reputation as a party resort with a man-made beach, it offers a variety of amenities that could appeal to travelers looking for a lively vacation atmosphere. This summary was generated by AI from Tripadvisor forum posts. See related posts Was this helpful? What are the airport transfer options in Jamaica? Transfer Companies and Options According to forum posts, travelers have several options for airport transfers in Jamaica. Popular transfer companies include JUTA (Jamaican Union of Travelers Association) and JTL (Jamaica Tours Ltd.), both offering desk services at Montego Bay airport for immediate bookings. These companies provide both private and shared transfers, with shared transfer costs ranging from $25 to $30 per person. Price and Booking Recommendations Some travelers recommend booking transfers in advance, especially for private rides or larger groups. Private transfers generally cost around $70 for up to four people, which can be more economical for groups compared to shared transfers. Booking through company websites or directly at airport desks upon arrival is a common practice. Special Considerations For those looking for luxury or specific needs, options like private limousines or taxis are available, with prices varying based on the company and service level. During the COVID-19 pandemic, some travelers suggested hiring COVID-certified drivers from lists available on official Jamaican tourism websites to ensure safety and compliance with health guidelines. This summary was generated by AI from Tripadvisor forum posts. See related posts Was this helpful? What are popular excursions in Negril? Excursion Activities Many travelers on the forum suggest a variety of excursions in Negril, including visits to YS Falls, the Black River Safari, and Calico Jack's Pirate Shack. The One Love Pub Crawl is frequently mentioned as an enjoyable outing, and some users recommend the sunset catamaran cruise to Rick's Cafe. Adventure and Nature For those interested in a mix of adventure and nature, Zimbali Culinary Retreats offers farm-to-table dining experiences in a scenic hilltop setting. Activities like snorkeling at Xtabi, exploring the Blue Hole, and visiting Little Bay for interactions with local culture and natural beauty are also popular. Local and Cultural Insights Travelers have called out specific local experiences such as the Rastasafari, which is an adventure tour that includes a ride through the countryside with stops to learn about local flora and culture. The Rastafarian experience, which includes a tour of a ganja farm and a vegan meal, is noted for its cultural depth. Relaxation and Viewing For more relaxed excursions, visiting the Negril Lighthouse, watching cliff divers at Rick's Cafe, and enjoying sunsets are recommended. These activities provide a laid-back yet engaging experience of Negril's scenic and vibrant atmosphere. This summary was generated by AI from Tripadvisor forum posts. See related posts Was this helpful? Tripadvisor is not responsible for these answers or any opinions in them. Please read full forum posts for more details and information. Frequently Asked Questions about Jamaica What is Jamaica known for? Jamaica is known for some of its popular attractions, which include: Treasure Beach Milk River Mineral Baths Nine Miles Benta River Falls Cane River Falls What is there to do in Jamaica? We recommend checking out these popular tours when looking for something to do in Jamaica: Party Catamaran: OpenBar, Music, Negril Beach, Rick's Cafe, Reef Atv Jungle Ride in Montego Bay Dunns River Falls and River Rapids Jamaica with Lunch Club Mobay Sangster Airport VIP Lounge with Priority Entry Horseback Riding and Swim Experience When is the cheapest time to visit Jamaica? If you're a more budget-conscious traveler, then you may want to consider traveling to Jamaica between June and August, when hotel prices are generally the lowest. Peak hotel prices generally start between March and May. © 2026 Tripadvisor LLC All rights reserved. Terms of Use Privacy and Cookies Statement Cookie consent How the site works Contact us Accessibility Statement This is the version of our website addressed to speakers of English in the United States . If you are a resident of another country or region, please select the appropriate version of Tripadvisor for your country or region in the drop-down menu. Tripadvisor LLC makes no guarantees for availability of prices advertised on our sites and applications. Listed prices may require a stay of a particular length or have blackout dates, qualifications or other applicable restrictions. Tripadvisor LLC is not responsible for any content on external web sites that are not owned or operated by Tripadvisor . Indicative hotel prices displayed on our “Explore” pages are estimates extrapolated from historic pricing data. Tripadvisor LLC is not a booking agent or tour operator. When you book with one of our partners, please be sure to check their site for a full disclosure of all applicable fees. Read more $ USD United StatesJamaica | National Geographic Kids Skip to content Search Shop Games Quizzes Personality Quizzes Puzzles Action Funny Fill-In Videos Amazing Animals Weird But True! Party Animals Try This! Animals Mammals Birds Prehistoric Reptiles Amphibians Invertebrates Fish Explore More Magazine history Science Space U.S. States Weird But True! Subscribe menu Please be respectful of copyright. Unauthorized use is prohibited. Please be respectful of copyright. Unauthorized use is prohibited. Please be respectful of copyright. Unauthorized use is prohibited. 1 / 3 1 / 3 Jamaica lies in the Carribbean Sea and has coastal beach regions popular with tourists. Jamaica lies in the Carribbean Sea and has coastal beach regions popular with tourists. Photograph by Ruth Peterkin, Dreamstime Jamaica Jamaica is a mountainous island in the Caribbean Sea about 600 miles (965 kilometers) south of Miami, Florida. FAST FACTS OFFICIAL NAME: Jamaica FORM OF GOVERNMENT: Parliamentary democracy CAPITAL: Kingston POPULATION: 2,812,090 OFFICIAL LANGUAGE: English MONEY: Jamaican dollar AREA: 4,411 square miles (10,992 square kilometers) MAJOR MOUNTAIN RANGES: Blue Mountains, John Crow Mountains, Don Figuero Mountains, Cockpit Country MAJOR RIVERS: Black River, Rio Cobre, Rio Grande GEOGRAPHY Please be respectful of copyright. Unauthorized use is prohibited. Jamaica is a mountainous island in the Caribbean Sea about 600 miles (965 kilometers) south of Miami, Florida . It is part of the chain of Caribbean islands called the Greater Antilles, along with Cuba , Hispaniola, and Puerto Rico. Jamaica was formed when the North American and Caribbean tectonic plates collided about 25 million years ago. Jamaica is the tip of a mountain rising from the sea floor. Nearly half of the island is more than 1,000 feet (330 meters) above sea level. There are lush rolling hills that are ideal for agriculture and coastal beach regions that are popular with tourists. Map created by National Geographic Maps A man steers a raft down the Martha Brae River in Jamaica. Photograph by Scott Griessel, Dreamstime Please be respectful of copyright. Unauthorized use is prohibited. PEOPLE & CULTURE Most of the population lives in the city and one third of all Jamaicans live in the capital of Kingston. More than 90 percent of the population is of African descent, but many other people have come from China, India, Germany, and Syria to find work on the island. Jamaica's motto is "Out of Many, One People." When most people think of Jamaica they think of Reggae, or "Ragged Music." The music was born in the 1950s and '60s from the musical styles of mento, ska, and rocksteady. The most famous reggae star was Bob Marley, who was backed by his group the Wailers. Other famous reggae stars include Desmond Dekkar, Jimmy Cliff, Peter Tosh, and Burning Spear. Jamaicans are spiritual people and follow many religions, including Christianity, Hinduism, Judaism, and Islam. Many are Rastafarians, followers of a Christian-based faith, which grew out of a civil rights movement in the 1930s. Rastafarians believe that Haile Selassie, Emperor of Ethiopia from 1916 to 1974, was their savior. Rasta men wear their hair in dreadlocks, believing that hair should not be cut, and wear clothing in red, gold, and green—the colors of the Ethiopian flag. NATURE The island is home to the endangered Homerus swallowtail, the largest butterfly in the Western Hemisphere. Its wingspan is 6 inches (25 cm), which makes this insect larger than many of the island's birds. Bird watchers enjoy the 250 bird species that can be seen on the island, including 26 birds that are found nowhere else. The vervain, the world's second smallest bird is found here. This tiny hummingbird is only 2.5 inches (8 cm) long. Jamaica's national bird is the streamertail hummingbird, or "doctor bird." It has long tail feathers and a scarlet bill. Jamaica boasts more than 200 orchids and 550 different ferns. One quarter of the 3,000 plant species are endemic, or native species. Years of development have decreased the habitats for wildlife on the island. The American crocodile, manatee, and iguana are rare now because they were hunted for meat and hides. Please be respectful of copyright. Unauthorized use is prohibited. Please be respectful of copyright. Unauthorized use is prohibited. LEFT: JAMAICAN FLAG, RIGHT: JAMAICAN DOLLARPhotograph by Maypen, Dreamstime HISTORY The Taino people arrived from South America in the seventh century and called the island Xaymaca, "land of wood and water," because of the green dense forest and the hundreds of fast-flowing streams that once covered the landscape. Christopher Columbus was the first European to visit Jamaica in 1494 and called it "the fairest island that eyes have beheld." The Taino people were enslaved and by 1600 were wiped out by disease or harsh treatment. The Spanish brought in slaves from Africa and ruled the island until 1655 when the British seized it. African slaves worked on the sugar plantations and were treated very cruelly by the owners. By the late 1700s, Jamaica became one of the largest slave markets for the Western Hemisphere. There were many slave uprisings and slavery was finally abolished in Jamaica in 1838. The island became independent in 1962. Watch "Destination World" Watch "Destination World" Now Playing 2:40 Africa Up Next 2:47 Antarctica Now Playing 2:38 Asia Now Playing 2:55 Australia Now Playing 3:14 Europe Now Playing 3:19 North America Now Playing 2:42 South America More to explore Countries U.S. states and territories facts and photos Get facts and photos of the U.S. states and territories, and the District of Columbia. Habitats Learn about the different natural environments of plants and animals. Destination World Our Earth is amazing! It’s made up of 7 huge landmasses called continents and each one is unique from the others. From the deserts of Africa to mega cities of Asia, watch as we explore the coolest places and most interesting facts about each of our continents. Legal Terms of Use Privacy Policy Your California Privacy Rights Children's Online Privacy Policy Interest-Based Ads About Nielsen Measurement Do Not Sell My Info Our Sites National Geographic 