out About GeekWire Advertise Contact Us Email Newsletters Reprints & Permissions Podcast LinkedIn Newsletter News Tips Toggle search box Search for: Search What happens here matters everywhere. Podcast LinkedIn Newsletter News Tips Amazon Microsoft Startups AI Science Tech Moves Sustainability Civic Geek Life Startup radar: Seattle founders tackle city permits, medical records, estate planning, cybersecurity GeekWire chronicles the Pacific Northwest startup scene. Sign up for our weekly startup newsletter , and check out the GeekWire funding tracker and VC directory . by Taylor Soper on Jan 24, 2025 at 7:00 am January 24, 2025 at 10:14 am Share Facebook X (Twitter) LinkedIn Email From top left, clockwise: Duckpins CEO Lauren Cappell; GovGoose CEO Perrin Myerson; MediScan CEO Kavian Mojabe; and Identient CEO Steve Tout. We’re spotlighting four new startups in Seattle that are looking to shake up various business processes with help from AI and other software tools. Check out past startup radar spotlights here , and send us an email at [email protected] to flag other companies or startup news. Duckpins This new Bellevue, Wash.-based startup is addressing the often messy and stressful experience of managing essential legal and personal documents. Duckpins lets users create a set of “foundational documents” — a will, estate documents, etc. — and execute them (sign, witness and notarize) digitally, all without needing an attorney. The startup, which just launched in Washington state, is riding tailwinds from legislation that authorizes electronic wills. The company was incubated at Seattle startup studio Jelly Collective and is led by Lauren Cappell , who previously worked at Amazon, CaaStle, and Thomson Reuters. GovGoose The world of municipal permitting can be complex. GovGoose wants to help. The Seattle startup pulls data from city codes on legal, permit, and zoning requirements. It also automates permit-related submissions to cities. The company, which is part of the latest Y Combinator cohort , is initially targeting the signage industry — companies that need to update signs and comply with rules. GovGoose CEO Perrin Myerson previously interned at AWS and LinkedIn, and spent four months at Civic News Company, a nonprofit focused on journalism. Identient Cybersecurity industry veteran Steve Tout previously held leadership roles at PwC, VMware, Oracle, and VeriClouds. Now he’s taking the startup leap with Identient, a Seattle-area company that launched last year and aims to help CISOs and CIOs with the business of cybersecurity. It’s focused on helping companies align business goals with identity and access management programs, or IAM. Tout developed a “Sentient IAM Framework” that acts as a scorecard for cybersecurity. MediScan Spending time at his father’s chiropractic office gave MediScan CEO Kavian Mojabe a first-hand look at the challenges doctors face in managing patient care. Now he’s leading a new Seattle startup that uses AI to help medical professionals review and analyze patient records. The company launched in July and has paying customers. Mojab previously worked at logistics startup INLT (acquired by Amazon) and video editing startup Scenery (acquired by Adobe). Track all of GeekWire’s in-depth startup coverage: Sign up for the weekly startup email newsletter ; check out the funding tracker and VC directory ; and follow our startup news headlines . Message from the Underwriter Future of AI: Perspectives on generative media for startups The ‘Future of AI: Perspectives on generative media for startups’ report features leading voices in AI including top founders, investors and Googlers. Hear their perspectives on the most critical generative AI innovations, media trends, opportunities, and challenges that startup leaders should consider when building and scaling in 2026. Get the report. Click for more about underwritten and sponsored content on GeekWire. More Startups Tech Moves: Amazon’s healthcare business gets new leader; Scott McFarlane leaves helm of Avalara Possible Finance rebounds, rebuilds, and reaches profitability as founders reunite for a new chapter CodeIntegrity raises $5M to put permanent guardrails on unpredictable AI agents Taylor Soper worked at GeekWire for more than 13 years as reporter, managing editor and editor, reporting on Seattle-area startups, Microsoft, Amazon, and the regional technology and investing scene. A native of Portland, Ore., and graduate of the University of Washington, he is now Director of AI House at AI2 Incubator. Follow him on LinkedIn . Share Facebook X (Twitter) LinkedIn Email Previous Story Madrona raises $770M for new funds — here’s what the Seattle VC firm is betting on Next Story ‘The Road Ahead’ at 30: What Bill Gates’ classic book about the future says about the world today Filed Under: Startups Tagged With: startup radar Latest Stories Read All Stories GeekWire Newsletters Subscribe to GeekWire's free newsletters to catch every headline Email address Subscribe GeekWire Daily - Top headlines daily GeekWire Weekly - Most-read stories of the week, delivered Sunday Breaking News Alerts - Important news as it happens GeekWire Startups - News, analysis, insights from the Pacific Northwest startup ecosystem, delivered Friday GeekWire Mid-week Update — Most-read stories so far this week, delivered Wednesday GeekWire Partner Content — Special offers and sponsored content from GeekWire partners Send Us a Tip Have a scoop that you'd like GeekWire to cover? Let us know. Send Us a Tip Related Stories Startup radar: Seattle-area tech companies build software for robotics, real estate, and more Startup radar: Early-stage companies getting off the ground in Seattle Startup radar: 5 early stage tech companies to know in Seattle Startup radar: Seattle companies build tech for marketing, food safety, games, and baby products Previous Story Madrona raises $770M for new funds — here’s what the Seattle VC firm is betting on Next Story ‘The Road Ah