rases Containing Rhymes Entries Near Related Articles Cite this Entry Citation Kids Definition Kids More from M-W Show more Show more Citation Kids More from M-W Save Word To save this word, you'll need to log in. Log In cock 1 of 5 noun (1) ˈkäk Save Word -- Synonyms of cock 1 a : the adult male of the domestic chicken ( Gallus gallus ) : rooster b : the male of birds other than the domestic chicken c : woodcock d archaic : the crowing of a cock also : cockcrow e : weathercock 2 : a device (such as a faucet or valve) for regulating the flow of a liquid the cock of an automobile radiator 3 a : a chief person : leader b : a person of spirit and often of a certain swagger or arrogance 4 a : the hammer in the lock of a firearm b : the cocked position of the hammer 5 usually vulgar : penis https://merriam.atlassian.net/browse/MWSITE-9211 -- see also: cock of the walk cock 2 of 5 verb (1) cocked ; cocking ; cocks intransitive verb 1 : strut , swagger did a lot of bragging and cocking after winning the game 2 : to turn, tip, or stick up a horse's tail cocking almost straight up 3 : to position the hammer (see hammer entry 1 sense 2b(2) ) of a firearm for firing transitive verb 1 a : to draw the hammer of (a firearm) back and set for firing also : to set (the trigger) for firing b : to draw or bend back in preparation for throwing or hitting a quarterback cocking his arm cock a bat c : to set (a mechanism, such as a camera shutter) for tripping (see trip entry 1 sense transitive 3 ) 2 a : to set erect a dog with one ear cocked b : to turn, tip, or tilt usually to one side cock one's head 3 : to turn up (something, such as a hat brim) https://merriam.atlassian.net/browse/MWSITE-9211 -- see also: cock a snook cock 3 of 5 noun (2) : tilt , slant cock of the head the jaunty cock of his hat https://merriam.atlassian.net/browse/MWSITE-9211 -- cock 4 of 5 noun (3) : a small pile (as of hay) https://merriam.atlassian.net/browse/MWSITE-9211 -- cock 5 of 5 verb (2) cocked ; cocking ; cocks transitive verb : to put (hay or something similar) into small piles https://merriam.atlassian.net/browse/MWSITE-9211 -- Synonyms of cock Relevance Noun (1) valve Verb (1) slope tilt angle tip lean heel Noun (2) tilt tip bend Noun (3) pile stack mound See All Synonyms & Antonyms in Thesaurus Examples of cock in a Sentence Noun (1) Quotes-- Extra Examples-- an automobile radiator cock Verb (1) Quotes-- Extra Examples-- cocked his head to the side as he listened to her quizzically Noun (2) Quotes-- Extra Examples-- a slight cock of his head suggested that he was listening in on our conversation Noun (3) Quotes-- Extra Examples-- a cock of hay Recent Examples on the Web Examples are automatically compiled from online sources to show current usage. Read More Opinions expressed in the examples do not represent those of Merriam-Webster or its editors. Send us feedback . Noun In Wyoming, where eleven of the nineteen primary river basins experienced the worst snowpack in recorded history, robotic cocks were deployed at a lek in Jackson Hole to lure females away from the airport and reduce the incidence of grousestrike. — Wyatt Williams, Harpers Magazine , 26 May 2026 Amaranth Amaranth, often called cocks comb or prince's tail, blooms from midsummer to the first frost. — Mary Marlowe Leverette, Southern Living , 4 Apr. 2026 Verb Fifty-three weeks earlier in Dallas, MacKinnon sat in his locker stall in a ragged gray T-shirt that looked like it had been chewed up by rabid raccoons, his left arm cocked on his left leg at a jagged angle, eyes flashing, face scowling. — Mark Lazerus, New York Times , 14 May 2026 With 8:28 to go, Kelly took Drury’s pass in the slot, cocked his stick back, and beat Wallstedt with a laser into the top shelf for a 3-2 Colorado lead. — Sean Keeler, Denver Post , 12 May 2026 See All Example Sentences for cock Word History Etymology Noun (1) and Verb (1) Middle English cok , from Old English cocc , of imitative origin Noun (3) Middle English cok ; akin to German dialect Kocke pile First Known Use Noun (1) before the 12th century, in the meaning defined at sense 1a Verb (1) 1542, in the meaning defined at intransitive sense 1 Noun (2) 1717, in the meaning defined above Noun (3) 14th century, in the meaning defined above Verb (2) 14th century, in the meaning defined above Time Traveler The first known use of cock was before the 12th century See more words from the same century Phrases Containing cock ball cock chaparral cock cock - a - doodle - do cock - a - hoop cock - a - leekie cock - and - bull story cock a snook cock a snook at cock of the walk cock snooks cock - up go off at half cock half cock turkey - cock Rhymes for cock balk baulk bloc bock broch brock calk caulk chalk chock clock croc See All Rhymes for cock Browse Nearby Words cocinero cock cock's egg See all Nearby Words Articles Related to cock 'Muskrat,' 'Helpmate,' and 6 More Folk... When logic meets language Cite this Entry Style Merriam-Webster.com Dictionary , Merriam-Webster, https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/cock. Accessed 1 Jun. 2026." MLA Merriam-Webster.com Dictionary , s.v. “cock,” accessed June 1, 2026, https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/cock." Chicago Merriam-Webster.com dictionary . Retrieved June 1, 2026, from https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/cock" APA Merriam-Webster.com Dictionary , https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/cock. Accessed 6/1/2026." Merriam-Webster “Cock.” Merriam-Webster.com Dictionary , Merriam-Webster, https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/cock. Accessed 1 Jun. 2026. Copy Citation Kids Definition cock 1 of 4 noun ˈkäk 1 : the adult male of a bird and especially the domestic chicken 2 : a device (as a faucet or valve) for controlling the flow of a liquid 3 : the cocked position of the hammer of a firearm a rifle at half cock https://merriam.atlassian.net/browse/MWSITE-9211 -- cock 2 of 4 verb 1 a : to draw back the hammer of (a gun) in readiness for firing cock a pistol b : to set or draw back in readiness for some action cock your arm to throw 2 : to turn, tip, or tilt upward or to one side cock one's head https://merriam.atlassian.net/browse/MWSITE-9211 -- cock 3 of 4 noun : tilt entry 2 sense 4 , slant a cock of the head https://merriam.atlassian.net/browse/MWSITE-9211 -- cock 4 of 4 noun : a small pile (as of hay) https://merriam.atlassian.net/browse/MWSITE-9211 -- Etymology Noun Old English cocc "cock, rooster"; probably in imitation of the sound it makes Noun Middle English cok "small pile" -- More from Merriam-Webster on cock Britannica.com: Encyclopedia article about cock Last Updated: 30 May 2026 - Updated example sentences Love words? Need even more definitions? Subscribe to America's largest dictionary and get thousands more definitions and advanced search—ad free! Merriam-Webster unabridged -- More from Merriam-Webster Word of the Day palatable See Definitions and Examples » Get Word of the Day daily email! -- -- -- Popular in Grammar & Usage See More 5 Verbal Slip Ups and Language Mistakes On ‘Suffice It to Say’ Regarding the Incorrect Use of 'Decimate' Is that lie 'bald-faced' or 'bold-faced'? The Difference Between 'i.e.' and 'e.g.' See More Popular in Wordplay See More Ten Words Ending with a Silent ‘T’ Strange Words for Body Functions Where does 'curiosity killed the cat' come from? What to Call the Inept, Incompetent, and Inferior The Words of the Week - May 29 See More Popular See More 5 Verbal Slip Ups and Language Mistakes Ten Words Ending with a Silent ‘T’ Strange Words for Body Functions See More Games & Quizzes See All Quordle Can you solve 4 words at once? Play Blossom Pick the best words! Play The Missing Letter A daily crossword with a twist Play Drop a Letter Quiz Drop a letter from a word to make a totally diffe... Take the quiz See All Merriam Webster Learn a new word every day. Delivered to your inbox! Help About Us Advertising Info Contact Us Privacy Policy Terms of Use Facebook Twitter YouTube Instagram ©