N ) [ T ] to move a part of your body upward or in a particular direction : cock your head He cocked his head on one side with a slight frown . cock a leg The dog cocked its leg (= urinated ) against a tree . to cock an ear / eyebrow SMART Vocabulary: related words and phrases Gestures & gesturing air punch air quotes bat beckon bird blow someone a kiss phrase flip someone off phrasal verb flip/give someone the bird idiom flourish gesticulate gesticulation non-verbal non-verbal communication non-verbally peace sign pump someone's hand idiom shake signing tongue wink See more results » cock verb ( PREPARE GUN ) [ T ] to push the necessary piece of a gun up into position so that it is ready to fire : He cocked his rifle and took aim . SMART Vocabulary: related words and phrases Guns artillery blaster blaze cannon cannonade cannonball carry a gun discharge gunfire gunnery gunpoint gunsmith kick plug rifle range salvo semi-automatically semiautomatic shoot someone down phrasal verb shoot up phrasal verb See more results » Idiom cock a snook at someone/something Phrasal verb cock something up (Definition of cock from the Cambridge Advanced Learner&apos;s Dictionary & Thesaurus © Cambridge University Press) cock | Intermediate English cock noun [ C ] us Your browser doesn't support HTML5 audio / kɑk / cock noun [C] ( BIRD ) Add to word list Add to word list a rooster (= an adult male chicken ) cock verb [ T ] us Your browser doesn't support HTML5 audio / kɑk / cock verb [T] ( TURN ) to turn a part of the body in a particular direction : He cocked his head to one side . cock verb [T] ( PREPARE GUN ) to prepare a gun so that it is ready for firing (Definition of cock from the Cambridge Academic Content Dictionary © Cambridge University Press) What is the pronunciation of cock ? &nbsp; What is the pronunciation of cocker ? Translations of cock in Chinese (Traditional) 鳥, 公雞，雄雞, （與鳥名合用）雄鳥，雄禽… See more in Chinese (Simplified) 鸟, 公鸡，雄鸡, （与鸟名合用）雄鸟，雄禽… See more in Spanish gallo, 