ewsletter Videos Rhodes iiD Talk Videos Partners Support iiD Contact Us Amy Liu Year: 2024 Topics: Data+ , Health Systems Operations Undergraduate Students I’m from New Orleans, LA. On campus, I’m involved in DTech, Duke Impact Investing, and the Duke Applied Machine Learning Group. I love poetry, reading, piano, and pilates! Related Projects Further Developing Duke’s Wearable Infection Detection Platform Topics: Data+ , Health Systems Operations Year: 2024 A team of students led by researchers in the BIG IDEAs Lab will optimize and further develop an existing cloud-based infection detection platform that populates and translates wearable data from a variety of sources. The project will involve working with existing wearable data pipelines (e.g., APIs) to collect, process, and... © 2026 Duke University, Rhodes iiD | Statement on Values & Culture | Accessibility Stay Connected Newsletter Contact Us FollowAmy Liu | Liberal Arts | UT - Austin College of Liberal Arts skip to content Amy Liu Professor and Interim Chair language politics; Eastern Europe, Southeast Asia, and Taiwan Students Prospective Students Academic Departments Office of the Dean News & Events Research Contact Liberal Arts ITS Resources for Faculty and Staff Emergency Information Web Privacy | Web Accessibility &copy; The University of Texas at Austin 2026Amy Liu | Brookings Experts Events Research Programs Research & Commentary Newsletters For Media About Us Leadership Careers Our Commitments Our Finances Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion BI Press Donate Home China Climate & Energy Iran 2026 Midterm Elections U.S. Economy Topics Business &amp; Workforce Cities & Communities Climate & Energy Defense & Security Education Global Economy & Development Health Care International Affairs Society & Culture Technology & Information U.S. Economy U.S. Government & Politics Regions Africa Asia & the Pacific Europe & Eurasia Latin America & the Caribbean Middle East & North Africa North America Search Home China Climate & Energy Iran 2026 Midterms U.S. Economy All Topics All Regions Experts Events Research Programs About Us Research & Commentary Newsletters Careers For Media Search Home Amy Liu Downloads Downloads CV Photo See More Contact Contact Metro Media Office [email&#160;protected] 202.238.3139 Share Share Bluesky Streamline Icon: https://streamlinehq.com Bluesky Search About About Downloads Downloads CV Photo See More Contact Contact Metro Media Office [email protected] 202.238.3139 Share Share Bluesky Streamline Icon: https://streamlinehq.com Bluesky Expert Amy Liu Nonresident Senior Fellow – Brookings Metro amy-liu-91371713 @amy_liuw Bluesky Streamline Icon: https://streamlinehq.com Bluesky Print About Toggle section navigation Sections Contact Metro Media Office [email protected] 202.238.3139 Downloads CV Photo See More Brookings Affiliation Program Brookings Metro Amy Liu is a nonresident senior fellow at Brookings Metro within the Brookings Institution. Liu has nearly three decades of experience as both a scholar and executive, committed to improving governance and public policies at the local, national, and global levels. Most recently, she served as the interim president of Brookings, guiding the institution for 18 months through a period of strategic assessment and change, leaving it stronger for its next chapter of leadership. She then stayed on as a presidential advisor to help with the transition and oversee critical cross-institution initiatives, such as the harnessing of AI and emerging technologies and tapping international perspectives in the institution’s global mission. Prior to July 2022, Liu served as vice president and director of Brookings Metro, which she co-founded in 1996. Today, the program is a leading resource for public and private sector leaders interested in promoting prosperous, just, and resilient communities. Liu is an expert on cities and metropolitan areas, as well as the interplay of national, state, and local policies in expanding economic opportunity. She has worked with leaders across the U.S. to translate research insights into action, and has written extensively about the future of post-pandemic cities, inclusive economic growth, state and local cooperation, and the role of federal policies in supporting place-based revitalization across urban and rural areas. Liu’s 2016 paper “Remaking economic development: The markets and civics of continuous growth and prosperity” spurred the development of new metrics for defining quality economic performance for metro areas and inspired widespread shifts in the goals and practices of many economic developers. Liu has published in The New York Times, The Washington Post, and Bloomberg News, and has been cited in a wide variety of national and local media platforms. Liu also served several stints in the federal government, including time at the U.S. Department of Commerce, the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development, and the U.S. Senate Banking Committee’s subcommittee on housing and urban affairs. Liu serves on several nonprofit boards and advisory councils, including JUST Capital , Equal Measure , the University of Illinois System President’s Advisory Council , and the Inclusive Abundance Initiative . Liu has received numerous accolades for her work over the years, including being named to Washington Business Journal’s 2021 class of Women Who Mean Business. Liu holds a Bachelor of Science degree in social policy with a concentration in urban studies from Northwestern University. In 2015, Liu completed the High Impact Leadership Program at Columbia Business School. Select experts -- Show results Select program Show results Select topics -- Show results Select regions -- Show results Search Filter by Topic Region Expert Research Program Date Language Sort by 10 20 30 40 results at a time Get the latest from Brookings Sign Up twitter facebook linkedin youtube instagram Brookings equips decisionmakers with nonpartisan research and policy strategies to create a more prosperous and secure country and world. Donate Research Programs Governance Studies Economic Studies Foreign Policy Global Economy and Development Brookings Metro About Us Leadership Careers Brookings Institution Press Contact Brookings Research & Commentary Experts Events Books Podcasts Newsletters Government Affairs Privacy Policy, Updated August 2024 Terms of Use, Updated August 2024 Copyright 2026 The Brookings InstitutionHome | Blackstar Skip to content Home Careers Blog Contact Us Home Careers Blog Contact Us News Announcing Our $12m seed round → The computer, made personal. We're building a new computer that knows you. We're building a new computer that knows you. Explore Careers → © 2026 Blackstar Computers, Inc.Careers | Blackstar Skip to content Home Careers Blog Contact Us Home Careers Blog Contact Us Careers Join Us. We're rebuilding computing from the ground up: the hardware, the software, and the interactions between them. This is a playground where nothing is siloed, and everyone gets to dive into a bit of everything. Every role here helps shape something no one has built before. Where We Come From Open Roles Engineering Software Engineer SF San Francisco SF Machine Learning Engineer / Researcher SF San Francisco SF Hardware (Electrical) Engineer Shenzhen · SF Shenzhen · San Francisco Shenzhen · SF Embedded Systems Engineer Shenzhen · SF Shenzhen · San Francisco Shenzhen · SF Mechanical Engineer Shenzhen · SF Shenzhen · San Francisco Shenzhen · SF Operations Technical Program Manager Shenzhen · SF Shenzhen · San Francisco Shenzhen · SF Chief of Staff SF San Francisco SF Design Industrial Designer SF San Francisco SF UI/UX Designer SF San Francisco SF Internships SWE Internship (Summer 2026) SF San Francisco SF MLE Internship (Summer 2026) SF San Francisco SF © 2026 Blackstar Computers, Inc.-- blackstarcompanies top of page HOME ABOUT Leadership Our Team Certifications Capabilities Statement Work With Us Subcontractors Contact SER